A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly ill-suited system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors continuously exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required decades of relentless effort.
This is the reason why it is essential that this year, an actively pursued approach be taken at both European and global levels.
In September, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at establishing a strong global system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that the States will be ready to commit to concrete and lasting action.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking during the year 2015.
Indeed, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to shelter, feed, and provide education for refugees, thereby reducing the temptation for them to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to 21 billion euros each year in the coming years.
But the financial implications of the crisis are incomparable to its human and political costs.
More than a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans afterward.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them asylum.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting a hateful nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the lived experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist activities.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they receive in social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support even within former liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote their own anti-immigration policies.
This situation has seriously undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million of refugees arriving on its shores has only managed to "relocate" 190,000 of them.
Border controls in six Schengen Area countries have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
To the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, the resolution of this crisis is not only a matter for Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
In any case, the EU is probably facing a threat to its own existence today, which it will only be able to overcome if it clearly demonstrates the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure channels allowing refugees to reach Europe.
It is not a matter of asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
Nevertheless, it is up to the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees it accepts, and to employ ordered mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would allow protecting migrants while safeguarding Europe (by enabling a thorough examination of applications).
Beyond a measure aimed at discouraging asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also allow projecting an image of solidarity toward frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
Another important aspect is that this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a strong global system to protect vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This objective will first require that more countries accept to host refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million refugees annually.
Several millions of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return to their home country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to accept a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
Since Canada has stated that it will host 50,000 Syrian refugees on its own this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will have to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current situation, these countries only provide a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading the infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are under pressure due to the arrival of a large number of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civil institutions.
But the effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these groups are still seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground by depriving newcomers of opportunities and by turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the contrary, if host countries manage to enthusiastically integrate migrants, everyone will benefit — including these countries (notably through inflows of money).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it was necessary to make a similar effort to build a better migrant protection system.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
